]]\n| [[Ford]]\n|-\n| [[2005 ARCA Re/Max Series|2005]]\n| September 5\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Frank Kimmel]]\n| [[Ford]]\n|-\n| [[2006 ARCA Re/Max Series|2006]]\n| September 4\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Ken Schrader]]\n| [[Chevrolet]]\n|-\n| [[2007 ARCA Re/Max Series|2007]]\n| September 3\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Ken Schrader]]\n| [[Chevrolet]]\n|-\n| [[2008 ARCA Re/Max Series|2008]]\n| September 1\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Frank Kimmel]]\n| [[Ford]]\n|-\n| [[2009 ARCA Re/Max Series|2009]]\n| September 7\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Parker Kligerman]]\n| [[Dodge]]\n|-\n| [[2010 ARCA Racing Series|2010]]\n| September 6\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Steve Arpin]]\n| [[Chevrolet]]\n|-\n| [[2011 ARCA Racing Series|2011]]\n| September 5\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Chris Buescher]]\n| [[Ford]]\n|-\n| [[2012 ARCA Racing Series|2012]]\n| colspan=3 align=center| Rained out\n|-\n| [[2013 ARCA Racing Series|2013]]\n| September 2\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Ken Schrader]]\n| [[Chevrolet]]\n|-\n| [[2014 ARCA Racing Series|2014]]\n| September 1\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Grant Enfinger]]\n| [[Chevrolet]]\n|-\n| [[2015 ARCA Racing Series|2015]]\n| September 7\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Grant Enfinger]]\n| [[Chevrolet]]\n|-\n| [[2016 ARCA Racing Series|2016]]\n| September 4 (Sun night race)\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Tom Hessert]]\n| [[Toyota]]\n|-\n| [[2017 ARCA Racing Series|2017]]\n| September 4\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Austin Theriault]]\n| [[Toyota]]\n|-\n| [[2018 ARCA Racing Series|2018]]\n| September 3\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Logan Seavey]]\n| [[Toyota]]\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.agr.state.il.us/dq/ Official DuQuoin State Fair Website]\n*[http://trackenterprises.com/ Track Enterprises Website]\n*[http://www.racing-reference.info/tracks/DuQuoin_State_Fairgrounds DuQuoin State Fairgrounds archive] at Racing-Reference\n\n{{USAC tracks}}\n{{USAC Stock Car racetracks}}\n{{USAC Silver Crown race venues}}\n{{ARCA tracks}}\n\n{{coord|37|58|58|N|89|13|23|W|region:US_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Motorsport venues in Illinois]]\n[[Category:ARCA Menards Series tracks]]\n[[Category:NASCAR tracks]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Perry County, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Perry County, Illinois]]\n\n{{Autoracing-venue-stub}}\n{{Illinois-stadium-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Motorsport venue\n| Name             = DuQuoin State Fairgrounds Racetrack\n| Nicnames        = \n| Time             = GMT-6\n| Location         = [[DuQuoin, Illinois]]\n| Coordinates      = \n| Image            = [[Image:Duquoinsat.JPG|275px]]\n| Image_caption    = \n| Capacity         = \n| Owner            = \n| Operator         = \n| Broke_ground     = \n| Opened           = 1946\n| Closed           = \n| Construction_cost= \n| Architect        = \n| Former_names     = \n| Events           = '''[[ARCA RE/MAX Series]]'''<br>[[General Tire Grabber 100]]<br>'''[[United States Auto Club|USAC Silver Crown Series]]'''\n| Miles_first      = True\n| Layout1          = Oval\n| Surface          = Clay\n| Length_km        = 1.6\n| Length_mi        = 1\n| Turns            = 4\n}}\n'''DuQuoin State Fairgrounds Racetrack''' is a one-mile (1.6-km) clay oval motor racetrack in [[Du Quoin, Illinois]], about {{convert|90|mi|km}} southeast of [[St Louis, Missouri]]. It is a stop on the [[Auto Racing Club of America|ARCA]] and [[United States Auto Club|USAC]] Silver Crown tours.\n\n==History==\nThe [[DuQuoin State Fair]] was founded in 1923 by local businessman William R. \"W.R.\" Hayes, who owned the fair and ran it. (It did not become run by the state of Illinois as a true \"state fair\" until the 1980s; it is now officially called the Illinois State Fair in DuQuoin, as opposed to the longtime one at state capital Springfield.) At the start Hayes had a half-mile harness-racing track on his 30-acre site, with wooden grandstands that seated 3000. In 1939 Hayes started buying adjoining stripmined land to develop its potential as parkland, replanting it and turning the strip pits into family-friendly ponds and lakes. He eventually expanded his little fairgrounds into 1200 acres.\n\nThe DuQuoin \"Magic Mile\" racetrack was constructed on reclaimed stripmine land in 1946 by W.R. Hayes. The track's first [[American Championship Car Racing|national championship]] race was held in September 1948.  In the second race on October 10, popular AAA National driving champion [[Ted Horn]] was killed in the fourth turn when a spindle on his championship car broke.  The national championship race for the [[United States Automobile Club|USAC]] Silver Crown dirt cars is held in his honor.\n\nIn 1957 the DuQuoin State Fairgrounds became the third longtime home of the [[Hambletonian Stakes|Hambletonian]], America's premier harness racing event (established 1926). The grandstands and bleachers were expanded to seat 18,000. When the Hambletonian left DuQuoin after 1980 to be raced at [[Meadowlands Racetrack|the Meadowlands]], the Fair became the home of the World Trotting Derby. This race was held from 1981 until it was discontinued after the 2009 race.   Both off-track and on-track betting are allowed.\n\nMusic concerts are also held at the track, especially during the state fair (in 2012 from August 25 through Labor Day, September 3). The stage is at center at the foot of the grandstand, backed up against the protective cyclone fence that shields the stands from the track.\n{{col-begin}}\n\n==Race winners==\n{{col-1-of-2}}\n===AAA/USAC Champ Car/Silver Crown race winners===\n''All winners were {{flagicon|USA}} American''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! Season\n! Date\n! Winning Driver\n! Chassis\n! Engine\n|-\n|rowspan=2| [[1948 AAA Championship Car season|1948]]\n| September 4\n| [[Lee Wallard]]\n| [[Louis Meyer|Meyer]]\n| [[Offy]]\n|-\n| October 10\n| [[Johnnie Parsons]]\n| [[Kurtis Kraft|Kurtis]]\n| [[Offy]]\n|-\n| [[1949 AAA Championship Car season|1949]]\n| September 3\n| [[Tony Bettenhausen]]\n| [[Kurtis Kraft|Kurtis]]\n| [[Offy]]\n|-\n|colsp